# Network Management in Linux

Network management controls interfaces, connectivity, DNS resolution, routing, and port monitoring.  
This document explains **what network management is**, **what it manages**, and **the essential commands**.

---

## 1. Management Area: Network Management

---

## 2. Definition – What Network Management Manages

Network Management controls:

- Network interfaces (IP, MAC, MTU)  
- Connectivity and routing  
- DNS resolution  
- Active ports and open connections  
- Downloading and testing network performance  

It ensures secure and stable communication between systems.

---

## 3. Commands List

---

### Network Interface Management

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `ip a` | Show network interfaces |
| `ifconfig` | Legacy tool to view interfaces |
| `ip link set eth0 up` | Enable interface |
| `ip link set eth0 down` | Disable interface |

---

### Connectivity Testing

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `ping host` | Test connectivity |
| `traceroute host` | Trace router hops |
| `curl url` | Fetch website/API |
| `wget url` | Download file |

---

### DNS & Domain Resolution

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `nslookup domain` | DNS lookup |
| `dig domain` | Detailed DNS info |
| `host domain` | Resolve domain to IP |

---

### Ports & Network Connections

| Command | Used For |
|--------|-----------|
| `netstat -tulnp` | Show open ports & active connections |
| `ss -tulnp` | Modern replacement for netstat |
| `ss -tn` | Show TCP connections |

---

## Summary

- Network management handles interfaces, connectivity, DNS, and ports.  
- `ip`, `ping`, `ss`, and `curl` are core networking tools.

